QUO WARRANTO VS IMPEACHMENT

Sabe ng batas, ang Quo Warranto ay puide maisampa sa lahat na impeachable at non-impeachable officials kapag ito sila ay hindi dapat qualified sa position sa simula plang. Ibig sabihin, ang Quo Warranto ay isang legal process na batayan kapag merong question sa qualification at maisampa ang Quo Warranto within one year upon the discovery that there is probable cause.

Ang Impeachment case naman ay puide maisampa sa mga impeachable officials for culpable violation of the Constitution, treason, bribery, graft and corruption, other high crimes, or betrayal of public trust. All other public officers and employees may be removed from office as provided by law, but not by impeachment (1987 Phil Constitution, article XI, section 2). 

Ang kaso na isinampa kay CJ Sereno, hindi na kailangan na umabot pa sa impeachment dahil sa umpisa palang ay questionable na yong kanyang qualification, sabe ng Justice and Bar Council (JBC). The Judicial and Bar Council‚Äôs (JBC) primary task is to recommend appointees to the Judiciary and the Office of the Ombudsman for the President‚Äôs perusal. The JBC aims to enhance the quality of the search, screening, and selection process, as well as insulate the process from undue influence of any kind. An important function of the JBC is the creation of a list of nominees for the position of Chief Justice of the Supreme Court. Sa kaso no Sereno, sinabe ng JBC na disqualified si Sereno dahil nalaman nito na under sa RA 3019 Sereno failed to comply with RA 3019 on two grounds:

1. That she filed her SALN four years late, in violation of the requirement that SALNs covering a given year should be filed on or before April of the year next to it.

2. That she filed an unnotarized SALN, i.e. she DID NOT SWEAR to its truthfulness, i.e. it is NOT A SWORN SALN, which is required by RA 3019.

Ang Quo Warranto ay puide isampa sa lahat na government officials if there is basis to believe that they are not qualified at the very start.

Bakit Quo Warranto ang naging kaso ni Sereno?

Dahil sa paniniwala na hindi dapat sya qualified na maging candidate sa pagiging member ng supreme court at maging chief justice dahil sinabe mismo ng Justice Bar Council (JBC) na disqualified sya dahil hindi sya nagsubmit ng kanyang SALN for many years at ang witnesses mismo laban sa kanya ay ang kapwa nya members ng Supreme Court at JBC. Dagpag pa, six years ago, si Sereno mismo ang nagsabe noon na ang hindi pagsubmit ng SALN ay isang basihan ng kaso. Ito ang sinabe ni Sereno noon, Under this law, failure to comply is prima facie evidence of unexplained wealth, which may result in the dismissal from service of the public officer.., 

CJ SERENO DUG HER GRAVE IN ADVANCE?

Chief Justice Lourdes Sereno, then an associate justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines, wrote a dissenting opinion on PSBank vs Senate of the Philippines Impeachment Court (GR No 200238).

In that dissent, Sereno wrote, Even prior to the 1987 and the 1973 Constitution, our laws have already imposed the obligation to disclose ownership of properties and assets.

Sereno added, Thus, as early as 1960, R.A. 3019, otherwise known as the Anti-Graft and Corrupt Practices Act, was promulgated, requiring from every public officer a detailed and sworn statement of their assets and liabilities.

Under this law, failure to comply is prima facie evidence of unexplained wealth, which may result in the dismissal from service of the public officer.., Sereno wrote.

To complete her point, Sereno then cited in the dissenting opinion two sections of RA 3019, one of which involves the requirement for public officials to file a SWORN SALN every April, covering the year immediately preceding the date of filing.

In light of her own declaration against interest, it must be recalled that Sereno filed her 2006 SALN four years late in 2010, as the stamp on the said document shows UP Diliman received it only in July 2010. To make matters worse, the SALN was not even notarized.

This shows that Sereno failed to comply with RA 3019 on two grounds:

1. That she filed her SALN four years late, in violation of the requirement that SALNs covering a given year should be filed on or before April of the year next to it.

2. That she filed an unnotarized SALN, i.e. she DID NOT SWEAR to its truthfulness, i.e. it is NOT A SWORN SALN, which is required by RA 3019.

QUO WARRANTO VS IMPEACHMENT

Sabe ng batas, ang Quo Warranto ay puide maisampa sa lahat na impeachable at non-impeachable officials kapag ito sila ay hindi dapat qualified sa position sa simula plang. Ibig sabihin, ang Quo Warranto ay isang legal process na batayan kapag merong question sa qualification at maisampa ang Quo Warranto within one year upon the discovery that there is probable cause.

Ang Impeachment case naman ay puide maisampa sa mga impeachable officials for culpable violation of the Constitution, treason, bribery, graft and corruption, other high crimes, or betrayal of public trust. All other public officers and employees may be removed from office as provided by law, but not by impeachment (1987 Phil Constitution, article XI, section 2). 

Ang kaso na isinampa kay CJ Sereno, hindi na kailangan na umabot pa sa impeachment dahil sa umpisa palang ay questionable na yong kanyang qualification, sabe ng Justice and Bar Council (JBC). The Judicial and Bar Council‚Äôs (JBC) primary task is to recommend appointees to the Judiciary and the Office of the Ombudsman for the President‚Äôs perusal. The JBC aims to enhance the quality of the search, screening, and selection process, as well as insulate the process from undue influence of any kind. An important function of the JBC is the creation of a list of nominees for the position of Chief Justice of the Supreme Court. Sa kaso no Sereno, sinabe ng JBC na disqualified si Sereno dahil nalaman nito na under sa RA 3019 Sereno failed to comply with RA 3019 on two grounds:

1. That she filed her SALN four years late, in violation of the requirement that SALNs covering a given year should be filed on or before April of the year next to it.

2. That she filed an unnotarized SALN, i.e. she DID NOT SWEAR to its truthfulness, i.e. it is NOT A SWORN SALN, which is required by RA 3019.

Ang Quo Warranto ay puide isampa sa lahat na government officials if there is basis to believe that they are not qualified at the very start.

Dagpag pa, six years ago, si Sereno mismo ang nagsabe noon na ang hindi pagsubmit ng SALN ay isang basihan ng kaso. CJ SERENO DUG HER GRAVE IN ADVANCE?

Chief Justice Lourdes Sereno, then an associate justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines, wrote a dissenting opinion on PSBank vs Senate of the Philippines Impeachment Court (GR No 200238).

In that dissent, Sereno wrote, Even prior to the 1987 and the 1973 Constitution, our laws have already imposed the obligation to disclose ownership of properties and assets.

Sereno added, Thus, as early as 1960, R.A. 3019, otherwise known as the Anti-Graft and Corrupt Practices Act, was promulgated, requiring from every public officer a detailed and sworn statement of their assets and liabilities.

Under this law, failure to comply is prima facie evidence of unexplained wealth, which may result in the dismissal from service of the public officer.., Sereno wrote.

To complete her point, Sereno then cited in the dissenting opinion two sections of RA 3019, one of which involves the requirement for public officials to file a SWORN SALN every April, covering the year immediately preceding the date of filing.

In light of her own declaration against interest, it must be recalled that Sereno filed her 2006 SALN four years late in 2010, as the stamp on the said document shows UP Diliman received it only in July 2010. To make matters worse, the SALN was not even notarized.

This shows that Sereno failed to comply with RA 3019 on two grounds:

1. That she filed her SALN four years late, in violation of the requirement that SALNs covering a given year should be filed on or before April of the year next to it.

2. That she filed an unnotarized SALN, i.e. she DID NOT SWEAR to its truthfulness, i.e. it is NOT A SWORN SALN, which is required by RA 3019.

JUSTICE MARTIRES: WE ARE NOT REMOVING A CHIEF JUSTICE

Supreme Court Associate Justice Samuel Martires did not mince words in his separate opinion on the Quo Warranto Petition versus Chief Justice Lourdes Sereno.

Specifically, the first several lines of Justice Martiress opinion reads:

It is well to state, at the outset, that we are NOT REMOVING A CHIEF JUSTICE because respondent Maria Lourdes P. A. Sereno, who has no valid appointment, is not the legitimate Chief Justice that the Filipino people perceive her to be.

Justice Martires himself provided the emphasis.

QUO WARRANTO VS IMPEACHMENT

Sabe ng batas, ang Quo Warranto ay puide maisampa sa lahat na impeachable at non-impeachable officials kapag ito sila ay hindi dapat qualified sa position sa simula plang. Ibig sabihin, ang Quo Warranto ay isang legal process na batayan kapag merong question sa qualification at maisampa ang Quo Warranto within one year upon the discovery that there is probable cause.

Ang Impeachment case naman ay puide maisampa sa mga impeachable officials for culpable violation of the Constitution, treason, bribery, graft and corruption, other high crimes, or betrayal of public trust. All other public officers and employees may be removed from office as provided by law, but not by impeachment (1987 Phil Constitution, article XI, section 2). 

Ang kaso na isinampa kay CJ Sereno, hindi na kailangan na umabot pa sa impeachment dahil sa umpisa palang ay questionable na yong kanyang qualification, sabe ng Justice and Bar Council (JBC). The Judicial and Bar Council‚Äôs (JBC) primary task is to recommend appointees to the Judiciary and the Office of the Ombudsman for the President‚Äôs perusal. The JBC aims to enhance the quality of the search, screening, and selection process, as well as insulate the process from undue influence of any kind. An important function of the JBC is the creation of a list of nominees for the position of Chief Justice of the Supreme Court. Sa kaso no Sereno, sinabe ng JBC na disqualified si Sereno dahil nalaman nito na under sa RA 3019 Sereno failed to comply with RA 3019 on two grounds:

1. That she filed her SALN four years late, in violation of the requirement that SALNs covering a given year should be filed on or before April of the year next to it.

2. That she filed an unnotarized SALN, i.e. she DID NOT SWEAR to its truthfulness, i.e. it is NOT A SWORN SALN, which is required by RA 3019.

Ang Quo Warranto ay puide isampa sa lahat na government officials if there is basis to believe that they are not qualified at the very start.

CJ SERENO DUG HER GRAVE IN ADVANCE?

Chief Justice Lourdes Sereno, then an associate justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines, wrote a dissenting opinion on PSBank vs Senate of the Philippines Impeachment Court (GR No 200238).

In that dissent, Sereno wrote, Even prior to the 1987 and the 1973 Constitution, our laws have already imposed the obligation to disclose ownership of properties and assets.

Sereno added, Thus, as early as 1960, R.A. 3019, otherwise known as the Anti-Graft and Corrupt Practices Act, was promulgated, requiring from every public officer a detailed and sworn statement of their assets and liabilities.

Under this law, failure to comply is prima facie evidence of unexplained wealth, which may result in the dismissal from service of the public officer.., Sereno wrote.

To complete her point, Sereno then cited in the dissenting opinion two sections of RA 3019, one of which involves the requirement for public officials to file a SWORN SALN every April, covering the year immediately preceding the date of filing.

In light of her own declaration against interest, it must be recalled that Sereno filed her 2006 SALN four years late in 2010, as the stamp on the said document shows UP Diliman received it only in July 2010. To make matters worse, the SALN was not even notarized.

This shows that Sereno failed to comply with RA 3019 on two grounds:

1. That she filed her SALN four years late, in violation of the requirement that SALNs covering a given year should be filed on or before April of the year next to it.

2. That she filed an unnotarized SALN, i.e. she DID NOT SWEAR to its truthfulness, i.e. it is NOT A SWORN SALN, which is required by RA 3019.

QUO WARRANTO VS IMPEACHMENT

Sabe ng batas, ang Quo Warranto ay puide maisampa sa lahat na impeachable at non-impeachable officials kapag ito sila ay hindi dapat qualified sa position sa simula plang. Ibig sabihin, ang Quo Warranto ay isang legal process na batayan kapag merong question sa qualification at maisampa ang Quo Warranto within one year upon the discovery that there is probable cause.

Ang Impeachment case naman ay puide maisampa sa mga impeachable officials for culpable violation of the Constitution, treason, bribery, graft and corruption, other high crimes, or betrayal of public trust. All other public officers and employees may be removed from office as provided by law, but not by impeachment (1987 Phil Constitution, article XI, section 2). 

Ang kaso na isinampa kay CJ Sereno, hindi na kailangan na umabot pa sa impeachment dahil sa umpisa palang ay questionable na yong kanyang qualification, sabe ng Justice and Bar Council (JBC). The Judicial and Bar Council‚Äôs (JBC) primary task is to recommend appointees to the Judiciary and the Office of the Ombudsman for the President‚Äôs perusal. The JBC aims to enhance the quality of the search, screening, and selection process, as well as insulate the process from undue influence of any kind. An important function of the JBC is the creation of a list of nominees for the position of Chief Justice of the Supreme Court. Sa kaso no Sereno, sinabe ng JBC na disqualified si Sereno dahil nalaman nito na under sa RA 3019 Sereno failed to comply with RA 3019 on two grounds:

1. That she filed her SALN four years late, in violation of the requirement that SALNs covering a given year should be filed on or before April of the year next to it.

2. That she filed an unnotarized SALN, i.e. she DID NOT SWEAR to its truthfulness, i.e. it is NOT A SWORN SALN, which is required by RA 3019.

Ang Quo Warranto ay puide isampa sa lahat na government officials if there is basis to believe that they are not qualified at the very start.

Bakit Quo Warranto ang naging kaso ni Sereno?

Dahil sa paniniwala na hindi dapat sya qualified na maging candidate sa pagiging member ng supreme court at maging chief justice dahil sinabe mismo ng Justice Bar Council (JBC) na disqualified sya dahil hindi sya nagsubmit ng kanyang SALN for many years at ang witnesses mismo laban sa kanya ay ang kapwa nya members ng Supreme Court at JBC. Dagpag pa, six years ago, si Sereno mismo ang nagsabe noon na ang hindi pagsubmit ng SALN ay isang basihan ng kaso. Ito ang sinabe ni Sereno noon, Under this law, failure to comply is prima facie evidence of unexplained wealth, which may result in the dismissal from service of the public officer.., 

CJ SERENO DUG HER GRAVE IN ADVANCE?

Chief Justice Lourdes Sereno, then an associate justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines, wrote a dissenting opinion on PSBank vs Senate of the Philippines Impeachment Court (GR No 200238).

In that dissent, Sereno wrote, Even prior to the 1987 and the 1973 Constitution, our laws have already imposed the obligation to disclose ownership of properties and assets.

Sereno added, Thus, as early as 1960, R.A. 3019, otherwise known as the Anti-Graft and Corrupt Practices Act, was promulgated, requiring from every public officer a detailed and sworn statement of their assets and liabilities.

Under this law, failure to comply is prima facie evidence of unexplained wealth, which may result in the dismissal from service of the public officer.., Sereno wrote.

To complete her point, Sereno then cited in the dissenting opinion two sections of RA 3019, one of which involves the requirement for public officials to file a SWORN SALN every April, covering the year immediately preceding the date of filing.

In light of her own declaration against interest, it must be recalled that Sereno filed her 2006 SALN four years late in 2010, as the stamp on the said document shows UP Diliman received it only in July 2010. To make matters worse, the SALN was not even notarized.

This shows that Sereno failed to comply with RA 3019 on two grounds:

1. That she filed her SALN four years late, in violation of the requirement that SALNs covering a given year should be filed on or before April of the year next to it.

2. That she filed an unnotarized SALN, i.e. she DID NOT SWEAR to its truthfulness, i.e. it is NOT A SWORN SALN, which is required by RA 3019.

For the information everybody kung bakit naging basihan ang qou warrant at hindi impeachment please be informed. Ito po ang ibig sabihin ng qou warranto at bakit ito applicable kay sereno:

Quo warranto is a special form of legal action used to resolve a dispute over whether a specific person has the legal right to hold the public office that he or she occupies.

Quo warranto is used to test a person‚Äôs legal right to hold an office, not to evaluate the person‚Äôs performance in the office. For example, a quo warranto action may be brought to determine whether a public official satisfies a requirement that he or she resides in the district; or whether a public official is serving in two incompatible offices.

INCORRECT. 

The SC Quo Warranto ruling against Sereno was  strictly in accordance with the provisions of the Constitution and the Rules of Court. Moreover, there have been two Quo Warranto rulings by the SC against IMPEACHABLE OFFICIALS. The justices could not suddenly be wrong now that the one involved is an Aquino appointee.

1. Article XI, Section 2 of the Constitution states that the President, the VP, the Members of the SC, the Members of the Constitutional Commissions, and the Ombudsman may be removed from office on impeachment for certain offenses. Note though that it did not say ‚Äùmay be removed on impeachment ONLY.‚Äù

2. Article VIII, Section 5 of the Constitution states that the SC has jurisdiction over Quo Warranto cases.

3. Pursuant to the provisions of section 5 (5) of Article VIII of the Constitution, the SC adopted and promulgated the Rules of Court in 1997.

4. Rule 66, Section 1 of the Rules of Court states that the government may commence Quo Warranto against a person who usurps, intrudes into, or unlawfully holds or exercises a public office, position or franchise.

5. Citing Sereno‚Äôs failure to submit the required number of SALNs to the JBC, the body that vets nominees for the positions in the judiciary, the SolGen challenged her integrity and the validity of her 2012 appointment.

6. There have been at least two Quo Warranto rulings by the SC involving IMPEACHABLE officials. One was in 1949 against the Comelec Chairman and a recent one was in 2012 against the COA Chairman.

The Senate Resolution indicates that the power to remove an impeachable officer, as in the case of a chief justice, is only thru impeachment proceeding. That while the constitution uses the word may be remove, yet it is exclusive since the word may be means may be remove or may be not --- as explained by former constitutionalist Atty Christian Monsod, the author of the said provision. Hence, the Senate as a collegial body is requesting the supreme court to reverse its decision on CJ Serenos ouster.

True, the Legislature is the only one who can impeach the President, Vice President, Chief Justice of the Supreme Court and other impeachable officials stated in the Constitution. The President and Vice President are elected by the people, so there is legitimacy in their position if not contested. In the case of the Chief Justice of the SC, who is an appointee of the Presiden, he/she has to be a leginate appointee to be considered legitimate. To become legitimate, he/she has to abide with all the requirements imposed by the constitution. If the appointee of the President has not abided by the Constitutional requirements, there is no legitimacy in his/her positition. So the constitional provision that only Congress can oust a sitting CJ of the SG doesnt apply in the case of CJ Sereno whose position is not legitimate. The quo warranto petition only cleared up the status of her position and to determine if there is reason for Congress to go to the rigmarole of the impeachment procedings.

7. Sana ngayon basbasan mo din si VP Robredo... please lang wag mo na patagalin.

Respondent (SERENO) curiously failed to mention that she, in fact, did not file several SALNs during the course of her employment in U.P. Such failure to disclose a material fact and the concealment thereof from the JBC betrays any claim of integrity especially from a Member of the Supreme Court. 

xxxx

Indubitably, respondent not only failed to substantially comply with the submission of the SALNs but there was no compliance at all. The contents of respondents Letter dated July 23, 2012 itself betray an exercise of dishonesty and disposition to deceive in an attempt to secure for herself the appointment as Chief Justice. In Ombudsman v. Pelino, We held:

Under the laws governing civil service, dishonesty is classified as a grave offense the penalty of which is dismissal from the service at the first infraction. A person aspiring to public office must observe honesty, candor and faithful compliance with the law. Nothing less is expected. This ideal standard ensures that only those of known probity, competence and integrity are called to the challenge of public service. It is understood to imply a disposition to lie, cheat, deceive, or defraud; untrustworthiness; lack of integrity; lack of honesty, probity or integrity in principle; lack of fairness and straightforwardness; disposition to defraud, deceive or betray. Dishonesty is a malevolent act that puts serious doubt upon ones ability to perform his duties with the integrity and uprightness demanded of a public officer or employee.
BAGSAK NA KASI KAYONG MGA DILAWAN.MBUTI NAMAN AT NATANGGAL SA PUWESTO YAN CJ SERENO NYO

In this case, it was found that respondent is ineligible to hold the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court position for lack of integrity on account of her failure to file a substantial number of SALNs and also, her failure to submit the required SALNs to the JBC during her application for the position. Again, one of the Constitutional duties of a public officer is to submit a declaration under oath of his or her assets, liabilities, and net worth upon assumption of office and as often thereafter as may be required by law. 335 When the Constitution and the law exact obedience, public officers must comply and not offer excuses. When a public officer is unable or unwilling to comply, he or she must not assume office in the first place, or if already holding one, he or she must vacate that public office because it is the correct and honorable thing to do. A public officer who ignores, trivializes or disrespects Constitutional and legal provisions, as well as the canons of ethical standards, forfeits his or her right to hold and continue in that office.

WHEREFORE, the Petition for Quo Warranto is GRANTED. 

Respondent Maria Lourdes P.A. Sereno is found DISQUALIFIED from and is hereby adjudged GUILTY of UNLAWFULLY HOLDING and EXERCISING the OFFICE OF THE CHIEF JUSTICE. Accordingly, Respondent Maria Lourdes P. A. Sereno is OUSTED and EXCLUDED therefrom.
The position of the Chief Justice of the Supreme Court is declared vacant and the Judicial and Bar Council is directed to commence the application and nomination process.
This Decision is immediately executory without need of further action from the Court.
Respondent Maria Lourdes P.A. Sereno is ordered to SHOW CAUSE within ten (10) days from receipt hereof why she should not be sanctioned for violating the Code of Professional Responsibility and the Code of Judicial Conduct for transgressing the sub Judice rule and for casting aspersions and ill motives to the Members of the Supreme Court.

SO ORDERED.

The sole law stating the qualifications of being a Justice in the Supreme Court is stated in Article VIII Section 7, nothing else. Nowhere in that provision states that they are required to submit SALN.  The only other two requirements not on that provision are 1) Being shortlisted by JBC and 2) Being appointed by the President from those shortlisted by JBC. 

Sereno met the qualifications set by the Constitution.  JBC asked the candidates for their SALN,  but this is simply a requirement they set on their guidelines. It is up to them to decide what to include in their guidelines,  no law dictates what they should put. Kung gusto nilang i-shortlist ay mga candidates lang na 56 pataas,  sila ang bahala dun (pero syempre inappropriate example yan haha). 

Now,  when they saw that most of the applicants would not be able to submit their complete,  previous SALNs,  they waived that requirement from their guideline. They waived it not only for Sereno. 

So,  they shorlisted Sereno and she was appointed by the President. She met all the requirements as per Constitution.

I painstakingly read the 153 paged Decision in the Quo Warranto Case against CJ Sereno. The bottom line of the Decision, that lead to the ouster, is that CJ Sereno failed to submit all her previous SALN from those years she taught in the UP College of Law and when she served as Republics Lawyer in International Arbitration Case. Though, after reading the full text, still not conclusive whether or not CJ Sereno deliberately failed or refused to file her SALN annually. 

At any rate, for the 8 Justices, failure to submit all previous SALN is counterintuitive to the integrity requirement to becoming a Chief Justice. They demanded a strict, full and complete compliance of this documentary requirement. With this, it makes me seriously think that probably these Associate Justices when they previously applied for such position (Associate Justice), may not be fully compliant at all. 

In such case, these Associate Justices should be subjected to the same standard they applied against CJ Sereno. Their qualifications, when they applied for Associate Justice, must be inquired in to too. As the ponente said, this Country should be continuously on the guard against impostors who unqualifiedly exercise sovereign prerogatives. I wonder if Sol Gen Callida would ever do so. I think there should be no double standard. 

If this becomes the trend, practically, all Government Offices, whether elective or appointive, will be left vacated.

From a top notch lawyer, Arnedo Valera on Quo Warranto, so that we may understand.

 Quo Warranto proceedings is constitutional and as a legal remedy it is recognized by our laws.

There so many case precedents where an elected or appointed official of the government is removed by Quo Warranto Proceedings where the election or appointment is invalid from the start or what we always call in legal term as void ab initio.

In which case a Quo Warranto proceeding will produce the legal effect of vacating an elective or appointive position. Although Article XI Sec. 2 of the Phil. Constitution enumerates officials who can be removed by impeachment, Impeachment is not the only way to remove an elected or appointed govt. official.

In the case of CJ Sereno, where there is a factual and legal basis that her appointment as CJ is invalid from the start or tainted with legal infirmities, Quo Warranto would lie as the right action. This is basic law. I do not understand where the legal idiocy of those opposing the quo warranto proceeding is coming from.

When CJ Corona was removed by impeachment, there was no issue that his appointment was invalid or void from the very start. Of course that impeachment proceeding is tainted with irregularities because monies exchange hands to support the impeachment. CJ Sereno is destroying the integrity of the Supreme Court and is becoming a distraction.

Either she resigns now or wait for the Quo Warranto ruling for her to vacate the position. There is no constitutional crisis if she refused to vacate. If I am the President , I can order her arrest to follow the rule of law i.e ordering her to vacate her position in the event a Quo Warranto proceedings prevail. Then as President, appoint a new CJ. Again, I am discussing a point of law consistent with case precedents on Quo Warranto proceedings in our legal history.- Claro Ganac

EX-CJ Sereno dug her own grave SIX YEARS IN ADVANCE 

Read and then comment your thoughts.  

QUO WARRANTO VS IMPEACHMENT

Sabe ng batas, ang Quo Warranto ay puide maisampa sa lahat na impeachable at non-impeachable officials kapag ito sila ay hindi dapat qualified sa position sa simula plang. Ibig sabihin, ang Quo Warranto ay isang legal process na batayan kapag merong question sa qualification at maisampa ang Quo Warranto within one year upon the discovery that there is probable cause.

Ang Impeachment case naman ay puide maisampa sa mga impeachable officials for culpable violation of the Constitution, treason, bribery, graft and corruption, other high crimes, or betrayal of public trust. All other public officers and employees may be removed from office as provided by law, but not by impeachment (1987 Phil Constitution, article XI, section 2). 

Ang kaso na isinampa kay CJ Sereno, hindi na kailangan na umabot pa sa impeachment dahil sa umpisa palang ay questionable na yong kanyang qualification, sabe ng Justice and Bar Council (JBC). The Judicial and Bar Council‚Äôs (JBC) primary task is to recommend appointees to the Judiciary and the Office of the Ombudsman for the President‚Äôs perusal. The JBC aims to enhance the quality of the search, screening, and selection process, as well as insulate the process from undue influence of any kind. An important function of the JBC is the creation of a list of nominees for the position of Chief Justice of the Supreme Court. Sa kaso no Sereno, sinabe ng JBC na disqualified si Sereno dahil nalaman nito na under sa RA 3019 Sereno failed to comply with RA 3019 on two grounds:

1. That she filed her SALN four years late, in violation of the requirement that SALNs covering a given year should be filed on or before April of the year next to it.

2. That she filed an unnotarized SALN, i.e. she DID NOT SWEAR to its truthfulness, i.e. it is NOT A SWORN SALN, which is required by RA 3019.

Ang Quo Warranto ay puide isampa sa lahat na government officials if there is basis to believe that they are not qualified at the very start.

Bakit Quo Warranto ang naging kaso ni Sereno?

Dahil sa paniniwala na hindi dapat sya qualified na maging candidate sa pagiging member ng supreme court at maging chief justice dahil sinabe mismo ng Justice Bar Council (JBC) na disqualified sya dahil hindi sya nagsubmit ng kanyang SALN for many years at ang witnesses mismo laban sa kanya ay ang kapwa nya members ng Supreme Court at JBC. Dagpag pa, six years ago, si Sereno mismo ang nagsabe noon na ang hindi pagsubmit ng SALN ay isang basihan ng kaso. Ito ang sinabe ni Sereno noon, Under this law, failure to comply is prima facie evidence of unexplained wealth, which may result in the dismissal from service of the public officer.., 

CJ SERENO DUG HER GRAVE IN ADVANCE?

Chief Justice Lourdes Sereno, then an associate justice of the Supreme Court of the Philippines, wrote a dissenting opinion on PSBank vs Senate of the Philippines Impeachment Court (GR No 200238).

In that dissent, Sereno wrote, Even prior to the 1987 and the 1973 Constitution, our laws have already imposed the obligation to disclose ownership of properties and assets.

Sereno added, Thus, as early as 1960, R.A. 3019, otherwise known as the Anti-Graft and Corrupt Practices Act, was promulgated, requiring from every public officer a detailed and sworn statement of their assets and liabilities.

Under this law, failure to comply is prima facie evidence of unexplained wealth, which may result in the dismissal from service of the public officer.., Sereno wrote.

To complete her point, Sereno then cited in the dissenting opinion two sections of RA 3019, one of which involves the requirement for public officials to file a SWORN SALN every April, covering the year immediately preceding the date of filing.

In light of her own declaration against interest, it must be recalled that Sereno filed her 2006 SALN four years late in 2010, as the stamp on the said document shows UP Diliman received it only in July 2010. To make matters worse, the SALN was not even notarized.

This shows that Sereno failed to comply with RA 3019 on two grounds:

1. That she filed her SALN four years late, in violation of the requirement that SALNs covering a given year should be filed on or before April of the year next to it.

2. That she filed an unnotarized SALN, i.e. she DID NOT SWEAR to its truthfulness, i.e. it is NOT A SWORN SALN, which is required by RA 3019.

ATTY. LOURDES SERENO PADDED RESUME?

In her concurring opinion in re: the Quo Warranto Petition vs Atty. Lourdes Sereno, Supreme Court Associate Justice Teresita Leonardo-de Castro wrote:

In respondents 2010 PDS and 2012 PDS, she indicated under Professional Experience that she held the position of Deputy Commissioner in the Commission on Human Rights (CHR) without specifying the period of her tenure.

PDS refers to the Personal Data Sheet, a bio-data/resume of sorts that details a candidates qualifications, including his/her professional experience.

De Castro added:

During the oral arguments, respondent practically admitted that there was no actual position of Deputy Commissioner in the CHR and it was merely her functional title in the predecessor office of the CHR, the defunct Presidential Committee on Human Rights. Her explanation is absurd as functions cannot be attributed to a non-existent position in the CHR.

In short, Atty. Sereno claimed in her de facto resume that she held a title that never existed. üòÇ

SOURCE: Supreme Court Associate Justice Teresita Leonardo-De Castros Concurring Opinion IN RE: The Quo Warranto Case against Chief Justice Lourdes Sereno.. Page 23. https://bit.ly/2G8DfmB

If we read Article VIII, Section 7:

Section 7. (1) No person shall be appointed Member of the Supreme Court or any lower collegiate court unless he is a natural-born citizen of the Philippines. A Member of the Supreme Court must be at least forty years of age, and must have been for fifteen years or more, a judge of a lower court or engaged in the practice of law in the Philippines.

(2) The Congress shall prescribe the qualifications of judges of lower courts, but no person may be appointed judge thereof unless he is a citizen of the Philippines and a member of the Philippine Bar.

(3) A Member of the Judiciary must be a person of proven competence, integrity, probity, and independence.

SALN is not mentioned as one of the qualifications. Yes, it is a requirement but the JBC members that time said that the rule on SALN was relaxed even before Serenos application for the CJ seat. CJ is one of the impeachable officials as stated in Article XI section 2

Section 2. The President, the Vice-President, the Members of the Supreme Court, the Members of the Constitutional Commissions, and the Ombudsman may be removed from office on impeachment for, and conviction of, culpable violation of the Constitution, treason, bribery, graft and corruption, other high crimes, or betrayal of public trust.
